    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The harness provides a strict accuracy advantage over self-consistency if and only if the critic's true-positive rate (TPR) strictly exceeds its false-positive rate (FPR) at the candidate level, making the global diagnostic odds ratio (DOR = TPR*FPR^-1*(1-FPR)*(1-TPR)^-1) the single sufficient predictor of strict improvement.\", \"mechanism\": \"For a set of n candidates with binary correctness y, the harness strictly improves over SC iff TPR > FPR. Proof: harness accuracy = SC + (TPR-FPR) * n_wrong. Since DOR is monotonic in (TPR-FPR), DOR > 1 iff TPR > FPR. The per-question structure is irrelevant; the global DOR captures the necessary and sufficient signal.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"global candidate-level TPR and FPR\", \"critic flag rate independent of question identity\"], \"excludes\": [\"critics evaluated at the question level\", \"critic correctness depending on question context\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"A critic with global DOR = 1.0 (TPR=FPR) but high question-conditional flag correlation produces a strict harness improvement of >5%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Two critics with identical DOR=3.0 but different per-question flag correlation structures produce harness-vs-SC deltas that differ by more than 15 percentage points\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This skeleton substitutes the mechanism from question-conditional alignment to global candidate-level TPR vs FPR, arguing the DOR is the sufficient predictor. The decisive experiment controls global DOR while varying per-question correlation to test if the latter has any residual effect.\"}",
      "changed_fields": ["claim", "mechanism", "scope", "forbidden", "prose_notes"]
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness advantage is strictly determined by the question-level variance of the base scorer's error margin, not critic alignment; strict improvement over SC requires high variance in the SC majority margin to provide enough leverage for the critic's filtering to flip wrong questions.\", \"mechanism\": \"Let m(q) = SC majority margin. Harness beats SC on wrong questions iff the critic flags enough candidates such that m(q) < flags. If m(q) is uniform, the critic cannot strictly improve SC without simultaneously breaking right questions. Thus, Var[m(q)] across the evaluation set is the sufficient condition for strict harness advantage.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"high variance in SC majority margin\", \"critic with fixed filtering threshold\"], \"excludes\": [\"uniform SC majority margin\", \"critics with question-adaptive thresholds\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Low margin variance but high critic alignment produces strict harness improvement >5%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"High margin variance but random critic alignment yields strict harness improvement >2%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This skeleton swaps the causal link from critic alignment to scorer margin variance. The decisive experiment varies the variance of SC majority margins while holding critic properties constant.\"}",
      "changed_fields": ["claim", "mechanism", "scope", "forbidden", "prose_notes"]
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"No fixed regime is sufficient; strict harness advantage is determined by the rank correlation (Kendall's tau) between the critic's continuous confidence score and the candidate-level semantic correctness, allowing the harness to selectively filter the worst-ranked candidates.\", \"mechanism\": \"For each candidate i, critic produces confidence c_i. Harness filters the bottom M candidates. Harness strictly beats SC iff Kendall's tau(c, y) > 0. If tau <= 0, filtering removes correct and wrong candidates at equal rates. Per-question discrete flag rates are insufficient; the global ranking correlation is the necessary and sufficient condition.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"continuous critic confidence scores\", \"global rank correlation between confidence and correctness\"], \"excludes\": [\"binary critic flag rates\", \"question-level grouping of candidates\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Kendall's tau = 0 but strict harness improvement >5% occurs due to question-conditional grouping of binary flags\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Kendall's tau > 0.5 but harness fails to strictly beat SC by a margin of at least 10%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This skeleton substitutes the mechanism from discrete flags to continuous confidence and rank correlation. The decisive experiment decouples Kendall's tau from discrete question-level flag rates.\"}",
      "changed_fields": ["claim", "mechanism", "scope", "forbidden", "prose_notes"]
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Strict harness advantage is impossible if the base scorer's accuracy p is sufficiently high, because the SC majority margin becomes robust enough that any critic flag rate capable of fixing wrong questions will necessarily destroy correct questions.\", \"mechanism\": \"Let p be candidate accuracy. The expected SC majority margin is proportional to (kp - (k-p)). As p -> 1, the margin grows. For a critic to flip a wrong question, it must flag > margin candidates. If p > 1 - 1/k, this required flag count exceeds the number of wrong candidates, guaranteeing false positives on correct questions. Thus, high p bounds strict improvement to zero.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"base accuracy p > 1 - 1/k\", \"critic with fixed flag rate phi\"], \"excludes\": [\"base accuracy p <= 0.5\", \"critics with perfect precision (phi=0)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"p = 0.9 and k = 5, but a critic with phi=0.4 and psi=0.6 yields strict harness improvement >2%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"p = 0.4 and k = 5, and no critic configuration yields strict harness improvement >0%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This skeleton swaps the scope to focus on high base accuracy as the limiting factor. The causal link is the robustness of the SC majority margin. The decisive experiment varies p and tests the bound on strict improvement.\"}",
      "changed_fields": ["claim", "mechanism", "scope", "forbidden", "prose_notes"]
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The determining factor for strict harness advantage is the critic's calibration error, specifically the Brier score; a critic with perfect calibration (Brier=0) guarantees strict improvement, while any miscalibration bounds the harness advantage below the theoretical maximum.\", \"mechanism\": \"Harness strictly beats SC iff the critic's predicted probability of correctness matches the true probability (perfect calibration). If the critic is perfectly calibrated, filtering candidates with predicted p < 0.5 removes exactly the wrong candidates. If miscalibrated, the filtering threshold is suboptimal. Thus, Brier score is the sufficient predictor of strict advantage.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"critic probability calibration\", \"Brier score as the measure of critic quality\"], \"excludes\": [\"binary critic flags\", \"ranking metrics like NDCG\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"A critic with Brier score = 0.3 but high question-conditional flag correlation produces strict harness improvement >10%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"A critic with Brier score = 0.0 (perfect calibration) fails to strictly beat SC\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This skeleton substitutes the mechanism from alignment to calibration error (Brier score). The decisive experiment varies critic calibration while holding question-conditional flag correlation constant.\"}",
      "changed_fields": ["claim", "mechanism", "scope", "forbidden", "prose_notes"]
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness advantage is determined by the temporal diversity of the sampled candidates; strict improvement requires high semantic diversity among wrong candidates to allow the critic to identify a discriminative feature for filtering.\", \"mechanism\": \"If all wrong candidates are identical, the critic must flag all or none, providing no selective advantage over SC. If wrong candidates are diverse, the critic can learn a feature present in wrong but not correct candidates. Thus, the entropy of the candidate distribution H(C) is the sufficient condition for strict harness advantage.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"high entropy candidate distributions\", \"critic using feature-based filtering\"], \"excludes\": [\"low entropy candidate distributions\", \"critics using non-feature-based heuristics\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Low entropy H(C) but high question-conditional flag correlation yields strict harness improvement >5%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"High entropy H(C) but low question-conditional flag correlation yields strict harness improvement >5%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This skeleton swaps the scope to candidate diversity and the causal link to feature discriminability. The decisive experiment varies the temperature of the base scorer to control candidate entropy.\"}",
      "changed_fields": ["claim", "mechanism", "scope", "forbidden", "prose_notes"]
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Strict harness advantage is determined by the mutual information I(C; Y) between the critic's binary flag C and the true candidate correctness Y; the harness strictly beats SC iff I(C; Y) > 0, making global mutual information the sufficient predictor.\", \"mechanism\": \"I(C; Y) = H(Y) - H(Y|C). If I(C; Y) = 0, the critic's flags are independent of correctness, and harness accuracy = SC accuracy. If I(C; Y) > 0, the critic's flags carry information about correctness, allowing the harness to selectively filter wrong candidates. The per-question structure is epiphenomenal; the global mutual information is the necessary and sufficient condition.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"global mutual information between critic flags and candidate correctness\", \"binary critic flags\"], \"excludes\": [\"question-conditional flag rates\", \"continuous critic confidence\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"I(C; Y) = 0 but strict harness improvement >5% occurs due to per-question grouping of flags\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"I(C; Y) > 0.2 but harness fails to strictly beat SC\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This skeleton substitutes the mechanism from question-conditional alignment to global mutual information. The decisive experiment controls I(C; Y) while varying the per-question flag correlation structure.\"}",
      "changed_fields": ["claim", "mechanism", "scope", "forbidden", "prose_notes"]
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"No fixed (p, phi, psi) regime is sufficient; the determining factor is the base scorer's per-question calibration, specifically whether the SC majority margin is inversely correlated with the question difficulty, allowing the critic to selectively intervene on borderline questions.\", \"mechanism\": \"Let d(q) be question difficulty. If SC margin m(q) is inversely correlated with d(q), SC is wrong on hard questions with small margins. The critic can then flag candidates on hard questions to flip the majority. If m(q) is uncorrelated with d(q), the critic's intervention is random. Thus, the correlation Corr(m, d) is the sufficient condition for strict harness advantage.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"base scorer calibration with respect to question difficulty\", \"inverse correlation between SC margin and difficulty\"], \"excludes\": [\"uniform question difficulty\", \"critic flag rates correlated with correctness\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Corr(m, d) = 0 but high critic flag correlation yields strict harness improvement >5%\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Corr(m, d) = -0.8 but harness fails to strictly beat SC despite a capable critic\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This skeleton substitutes the mechanism from critic alignment to base scorer calibration with respect to difficulty. The decisive experiment varies the correlation between SC margin and difficulty while holding critic properties constant.\"}",
      "changed_fields": ["claim", "mechanism", "scope", "forbidden", "prose_notes"]
    }
  ]
